# Pull request descriptions

When the user asks for a PR description, pull request body, or review summary for a GitHub PR, **use this exact markdown skeleton**. Replace placeholders with real content; omit sections only if truly N/A (say so briefly in Summary).

## Template

```markdown
# PR Description — {TICKET_ID}

---

## Summary

{One paragraph: what this PR does, why, and the user-facing behavior change. Reference the ticket ID. Mention key implementation approach (e.g., "CSS-only", "no new dependencies"). Call out what is NOT changed if relevant.}

---

## What Changed

- **{Area 1}**: {Concise description of changes in this area. Include specific values, class names, props, config — be precise enough that a reviewer knows what to look for.}
- **{Area 2}**: {Same format. Group by logical area: Frontend, Backend, Tests, Config, Infra, etc.}
- **Tests**: {What tests were added/updated. Note any testing limitations (e.g., "not asserted in JSDOM due to mocked CSS").}

---

## Files Modified

| Area   | File               | Change                                           |
| ------ | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------ |
| {Area} | `{path/to/file}`   | {Brief description of what changed in this file} |
| {Area} | `{path/to/file}`   | {Brief description}                              |

---
```

## Rules

- Keep **headings and horizontal rules** as shown so PRs stay consistent.
- **TICKET_ID**: use the ticket from the branch or user (e.g. `LEGAL-001`, `JIRA-123`); if unknown, use `TBD` and note it in Summary.
- **Files Modified** table: list every touched file that matters for review; group **Area** (e.g. Frontend, Docs, CI).
